#1 Stage IIIA colon cancer
I had a very long discussion with the patient about the need for adjuvant chemotherapy to decrease her risk of developing recurrent disease.  We talked about the standard regimen of modified FOLFOX, and we would recommend 12 cycles.  She will definitely need a port placed because of the infusion of 5-FU.  Patient would like to be treated closer to her hometown in Bison Cuero.  The closest oncologist there is Dr. Tiffany Gregg in New York.  I did call over to make the referral for her, but the closest appointment I could get was July 21, 2010.  Because the patient is exactly four weeks out from her surgery now, I would like for her to be started in less than six-weeks and within the next two-weeks.  Therefore, we will go ahead and set the patient up to have a port placed within the next week and then start chemotherapy shortly thereafter.  She will see me and be followed for her chemotherapy until she is able to transfer her care over to Dr. Tiffany Gregg in New York.  We went over the regimen as well as to expect the side-effects of FOLFOX, and the patient asked appropriate questions.  I did spend over 60 minutes with the patient, examining her, going over the plan of care, discussing the chemotherapy, the side-effects, as well as making the referral in the patient's presence.
The patient was seen and discussed with my staff, Dr. Leslie Hall.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: Yes, not on file at Affiliated Hospital.

