[start section id="20103"]

This is a pleasant 61-year-old female from Bison Cuero, who was recently-diagnosed with stage III colon cancer.  Patient was in her usual state of health until May 2010 where on routine colonoscopy she was found to have a malignant polyp.  She underwent surgery by Dr. Leslie Mosley on June 3, 2010, when she had a laparoscopic subtotal colectomy and was found to have a-1.3-cm grade 3 (out of 4) adenocarcinoma with 4 out of 56 lymph nodes positive.  Further staging workup was completely negative.  Patient did well postoperatively, but on June 10, 2010, she was readmitted with a partial small-bowel obstruction which was just managed conservatively, and she was discharged on June 18, 2010.
Patient has completely recovered and is eating a normal diet and has maintained her weight.  She denied fevers, chills, nausea, vomiting, or any other symptom and is ready to proceed with further treatment.

[end section id="20103"]

